race_comments: Ryan Blaney won the UNOH 200 presented by ZLOOP at Bristol Motor Speedway, his fourth victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 36 (missed driver introductions).

Joey Logano won the Kroger 250 at Martinsville Speedway, his first victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race, the following cars dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: #1 and #11 (unapproved adjustments).

Matt Crafton won the Kroger 200, his 10th career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory and second at Martinsville Speedway. Prior to the start of the race, the following cars dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 15 and 74 (unapproved adjustments).

John Hunter Nemechek won the American Ethanol E15 225, his first career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: Nos. 6, 74 (missed drivers meeting); Nos. 14, 54 (engine change); Nos. 45, 08 (missed driver intros).
Matt Crafton won the Ford EcoBoost 200, his 11th career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, no trucks dropped to the rear of the field.

Matt Crafton won the Toyota Tundra 250 at Kansas Speedway, his seventh victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series and second at the track. Prior to the start of the race, the following cars dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 19 and 29 (backup trucks), No. 50 (unapproved adjustments).

John Wes Townley won the Rhino Linings 350, his first career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the 
rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 07 (missing drivers meeting) and No. 4 (engine change).

Matt Crafton won the WinStar World Casino & Resort 400 at Texas Motor Speedway, his eighth career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. No trucks dropped to the rear of the field prior to the start of the race.

Erik Jones won the WinStar World Casino & Resorts 350, his seventh career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 02 (unapproved adjustments).

race_name: American Ethanol presents the Drivin for Linemen 200 brought to you by Ameren
race_comments: Cole Custer won the American Ethanol presents the Drivin for Linemen 200 brought to you by Ameren at Gateway Motorsports Park, his second win in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race the following trucks dropped to rear of the field for the reasons indicated:No. 08 (back-up truck), and No. 1 (unapproved adjustments)

Matt Crafton won the UNOH 225, his ninth career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, no trucks dropped to the rear of the field. The race was called five laps short of completion due to a damaged catchfence caused by an accident involving the No. 11 truck.

Timothy Peters won the Fred's 250, his ninth career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 08 (unapproved adjustments).

Timothy Peters won the Lucas Oil 150, his 10th career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 74 (transmission change); Nos. 02, 08 (unapproved adjustments).

Tyler Reddick won the Lucas Oil 200, his second career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reason indicated: No. 33 (unapproved adjustments).

Tyler Reddick won the NextEra Energy Resources 250 at Daytona International Speedway, his first victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race, the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field: #17 (backup car), #6, #51 (unapproved adjustments during impound).

Matt Crafton won the Hyundai Construction Equipment 200 at Atlanta Motor Speedway, his sixth victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series and first at Atlanta. Prior to the start of the race, the following cars dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: #1 (unapproved adjustments), #74 and #94 (missed the drivers meeting), #39 and #75 (missed driver introductions).

race_name: Careers for Veterans 200 Presented by Cooper Standard and Brad Keselowski's Checkered Flag Foundation
race_comments: Kyle Busch won the Careers for Veterans 200 Presented by The Cooper Standard Foundation & Brad Keselowski's Checkered Flag Foundation, his 44th career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, no trucks dropped to the rear of the field.
Austin Dillon won the UNOH 175, his seventh career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, no trucks dropped to the rear of the field.

Kasey Kahne won the NC Education Lottery 200, his fifth victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race, the following 
cars dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: Nos. 00, 23, 54 (unapproved adjustments); Nos. 1, 4, 45, 74 (late to drivers meeting).
Kyle Busch won the Pocono Mountains 150, his 43rd career NASCAR Camping World Truck Series victory. Prior to the start of the race, no trucks dropped to the rear of the field.

Erik Jones has won the American Ethanol 200 presented by Enogen, his fifth victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: Nos. 1 and 74 (unapproved adjustments).

Christopher Bell has won the 1-800-Car-Cash Mud Summer Classic, his first victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the 
start of the race the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: No. 11 (unapproved adjustments), No. 82 
(missed driver introductions).

Erik Jones won the Silverado 250 at Canadian Tire Motorsports Park, his sixth victory in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series. Prior to the start of the race the following trucks dropped to the rear of the field for the reasons indicated: Nos. 1, 10, 44 (unapproved adjustments).
